time_trend_data.indicator_name: Carbon Monoxide Emergency Department Visits (Other Causes)

Compare.graph_title: Trends in Carbon Monoxide Emergency Department Visits - Other Causes - Age-Adjusted Rate 2005 to 2013

info.info_name: Carbon Monoxide Emergency Department Visits (Other Causes)
info.info_how_calculated: NYC residents treated in an emergency department (ED), including those who were admitted as inpatients after being seen in an ED, having the ICD-9 diagnosis code for carbon monoxide poisoning, 986 and any of the following codes: E818, E825, E838, E844, E867, E868.0-1, E869.9 or having E868.2- E868.9 codes (regardless of the presence or absence of 986). Must not have fire-related injury codes E890.0-E899.9. Cannot have any intentional injury code within E950.0-E979.9 or E990-E999. Counts are summed by 5-year age groups and divided by the population in each age group, using NYC DOHMH intercensal estimates; quotients are multiplied by the proportion of the 2000 US population in each age group. Age-adjusted rate is the sum of the weighted age-specific rates; expressed as cases per million residents.
info.info_source: New York State Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System (SPARCS) Deidentified Hospital Discharge Data, United States Census
